Box Plot

In [484]:
#Box Plot of product category based on price
fig = px.box(df, x = 'category', y = 'price', 
             title = 'Box Plot of Price For Different Product Categories')
fig.update_xaxes(title = 'Product Category')
fig.update_yaxes(title = 'Price')
fig.update_traces(boxmean = True, marker_color = 'darkslategray')
fig.show()
A box plot is a statistical representation of the distribution of a variable through its quartiles. The ends of the box represent the lower and upper quartiles, while the median (second quartile) is marked by a line inside the box and the mean price of each item is represented by the dotted lines inside the box. The box plot also represent the minimum and maximum price of each item, shown by both the ends of the plot.
In [486]:
#Box Plot of product category based on total sales
fig = px.box(new_df, x = 'category', y = 'total_sales', 
             title = 'Box Plot of Total Sales For Different Product Categories')
fig.update_xaxes(title = 'Product Category')
fig.update_yaxes(title = 'Total Sales')
fig.update_traces(boxmean = True, marker_color = 'peru')
The box plot of total sales and product category indicates that there are some outliers in sales of some product, indicated by the dots outside the whiskers, that is, the sales is numerically distant from the rest of the sales value. That is, there are product categories which have too high sale or low sale compared to the rest of the sales value. The overall spread as shown by the extreme values at the end of two whiskers shows the range of dispersion. Larger ranges indicate wider distribution, that is, more scattered data. The graph of each product category shows that the sales are more scattered.
